1
00:00:00,760 --> 00:00:02,790
<i>(MUSIC PLAYING ON STEREO)</i>

2
00:00:06,440 --> 00:00:11,000
Wait. We shouldn't...
We shouldn't be doing this.

3
00:00:11,510 --> 00:00:14,170
What? You're not having fun?

4
00:00:14,610 --> 00:00:16,340
It's not that. I just...

5
00:00:16,410 --> 00:00:18,180
Rather be with the boys?

6
00:00:18,810 --> 00:00:20,480
No.

7
00:00:20,550 --> 00:00:22,380
Well, then come on.

8
00:00:23,720 --> 00:00:25,310
(BANGING)

9
00:00:35,430 --> 00:00:36,690
You kids need any help?

10
00:00:36,770 --> 00:00:38,170
No. No, we're fine.

11
00:00:38,230 --> 00:00:39,390
Car trouble?

12
00:00:39,470 --> 00:00:40,560
No.

13
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:42,330
Then why are you here?

14
00:00:42,410 --> 00:00:43,670
We're just talking.

15
00:00:44,910 --> 00:00:47,740
Does she do all the talking?

16
00:00:47,810 --> 00:00:49,140
Most of it.

17
00:00:51,250 --> 00:00:53,340
I know what that's like.

18
00:00:54,020 --> 00:00:56,350
I'm gonna come back
through here in 10 minutes,

19
00:00:56,420 --> 00:01:00,050
and if you're still here,
I'm gonna call your parents.

20
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:03,490
Yes, sir. Thank you.

21
00:01:12,030 --> 00:01:14,330
Now, where were we?

22
00:01:14,400 --> 00:01:16,300
We were going.

23
00:01:16,370 --> 00:01:17,960
In nine minutes.

24
00:01:35,390 --> 00:01:36,880
Wait...

25
00:01:36,960 --> 00:01:38,550
Stevie? What's wrong?

26
00:01:44,270 --> 00:01:45,700
Oh, my God!

27
00:01:48,470 --> 00:01:51,630
Help! Someone help me!

28
00:03:14,490 --> 00:03:15,860
(WATER SPLASHING)

29
00:03:29,740 --> 00:03:32,430
Sixteen-year-old
with respiratory arrest.

30
00:03:32,940 --> 00:03:35,410
The only thing I hate more
than a thief
is a crippled thief.

31
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:37,500
Yeah, me, too.
No sign of trauma, no history

32
00:03:37,580 --> 00:03:39,340
of asthma or...
Who the hell is J. Whitner?

33
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:43,650
No idea. Stevie Lipa's EKG
and echocardiogram
were normal, but...

34
00:03:43,750 --> 00:03:46,050
Normal is good. Send him home.

35
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:50,390
J. Whitner, doctor.
Who is he,
and where do I find him?

36
00:03:50,460 --> 00:03:52,450
She's the new researcher,
works with Ereshevsky.

37
00:03:52,530 --> 00:03:54,290
Is she hot?
She's in a wheelchair.

38
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:55,460
Doesn't mean she's not hot.

39
00:03:55,530 --> 00:03:56,960
Just means
she can't bend over,

40
00:03:57,030 --> 00:03:59,230
so Cuddy has to
bend over backwards.

41
00:03:59,300 --> 00:04:03,740
Sixteen-year-old kid.
ER workup revealed
a bloody pleural effusion.

42
00:04:03,810 --> 00:04:05,140
That's odd.

43
00:04:05,210 --> 00:04:06,640
Yeah, that occurred to me.

44
00:04:06,710 --> 00:04:08,640
What took you so long
to mention it?

45
00:04:08,710 --> 00:04:10,440
No tumors or pneumonia
on the CT.

46
00:04:10,510 --> 00:04:12,710
He passed out
while making out.

47
00:04:12,780 --> 00:04:15,650
If he's into sex,
drugs and rock and roll
can't be that far behind.

48
00:04:15,720 --> 00:04:17,080
I'm guessing cocaine.

49
00:04:17,150 --> 00:04:18,310
Tox screen was clean.

50
00:04:18,390 --> 00:04:20,790
Just means he wasn't on drugs,
not that he hasn't been
using drugs.

51
00:04:20,860 --> 00:04:23,720
Looks like a plumbing problem
to me. Leaky pipes.

52
00:04:23,790 --> 00:04:26,260
If he popped an aneurysm,
he'd be in the morgue,
not the ER.

53
00:04:26,330 --> 00:04:28,660
That's why you're gonna
do a venogram
instead of an arteriogram.

54
00:04:28,730 --> 00:04:31,060
This is not
a high-pressure burst.
It's a low-pressure leak.

55
00:04:31,130 --> 00:04:34,000
Still could've been drugs
that caused the pipes
to corrode in the first place.

56
00:04:34,070 --> 00:04:35,500
So go look under his mattress.

57
00:04:35,570 --> 00:04:39,270
See if he's got any pills
or powder stashed
with the hand lotion.

58
00:04:53,790 --> 00:04:58,280
Sweet ride. I asked for
the one with the sissy bar
and the banana seat,

59
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:02,850
but Santa gave me
this instead. Guess that's
what I get for being naughty.

60
00:05:03,700 --> 00:05:05,290
You must be Dr. House.

61
00:05:05,370 --> 00:05:06,430
Yeah.

62
00:05:07,100 --> 00:05:10,130
So looks like there's been
some sort of mix-up
at the parking office.

63
00:05:10,210 --> 00:05:12,000
They had to move me closer
to the door.

64
00:05:12,070 --> 00:05:15,600
Had to? You don't look
like the type to
pull a weapon.

65
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:17,610
Wheelchair.
Cane.

66
00:05:18,010 --> 00:05:21,140
I think you should do the
honorable thing and let me
have my space back.

67
00:05:21,220 --> 00:05:24,520
Oh, well,
since you asked so nicely,
wheelchair.

68
00:05:25,120 --> 00:05:28,720
Cane.
Walking long distances
makes my leg hurt.

69
00:05:28,790 --> 00:05:30,380
And it's easy for me?

70
00:05:30,460 --> 00:05:32,790
Of course not.
Pushing that little lever?

71
00:05:32,860 --> 00:05:37,060
The muscles must burn.
I'm sure the last 10 yards
are pure torture.

72
00:05:37,130 --> 00:05:39,330
Crossing the parking lot
is dangerous.
Cars can't see me.

73
00:05:39,400 --> 00:05:41,770
You ever hit a patch
of black ice with a cane?

74
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:45,530
No, gosh,
on account of the fact
that I can't walk.

75
00:05:45,610 --> 00:05:48,510
Maybe you should ask
the parking office
for some crampons.

76
00:05:48,580 --> 00:05:53,510
This is about who can most
easily cross the parking lot.
You're the winner.

77
00:05:53,580 --> 00:05:56,680
Oh, and the prize
is apparently a parking space.

78
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:09,060
There's still no answer
at either one of your
parent's cell numbers.

79
00:06:09,130 --> 00:06:11,430
Is there any other way
we might be
able to contact them?

80
00:06:11,500 --> 00:06:14,960
No, they're in a conference.

81
00:06:15,370 --> 00:06:17,310
They probably had
to turn them off or something.

82
00:06:17,370 --> 00:06:19,500
What does it matter
where they are?
I mean, he's in pain.

83
00:06:19,580 --> 00:06:20,700
You gotta do something.

84
00:06:20,780 --> 00:06:22,040
We need them to sign this.

85
00:06:22,110 --> 00:06:24,240
Why can't he just
sign the papers? He's 16.

86
00:06:24,310 --> 00:06:25,680
Still not an adult.

87
00:06:25,750 --> 00:06:28,620
Then call my parents.
They know him, and they'll
take responsibility,

88
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:30,310
do whatever you need.
I can't. It won't...

89
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:33,120
You can't just let him
sit here in agony until
his parents finally decide...

90
00:06:33,190 --> 00:06:35,180
Leah, it's okay.

91
00:06:35,260 --> 00:06:37,020
No, it's not.

92
00:06:39,330 --> 00:06:42,660
I feel like there's an anvil
sitting on my chest.

93
00:06:43,030 --> 00:06:44,590
(MONITOR BEEPING)

94
00:06:59,850 --> 00:07:04,290
You win. I'm doing the
venogram now. We'll deal
with the fallout later.

95
00:07:08,720 --> 00:07:10,920
(COUGHING)

96
00:07:15,930 --> 00:07:17,800
My fingers feel wet.

97
00:07:17,870 --> 00:07:20,390
That's just the dye.
Your nerves can't
tell the difference

98
00:07:20,470 --> 00:07:22,990
between the cold
inside your body and
the wet outside your body.

99
00:07:23,070 --> 00:07:27,570
The nerves can't tell the
difference, or the brain can't
interpret the difference?

100
00:07:27,640 --> 00:07:31,010
A little of both.
You like science?

101
00:07:35,620 --> 00:07:37,780
Looks like
a diffusion pattern.

102
00:07:37,850 --> 00:07:40,520
That's because it's
the venous side. Low pressure.

103
00:07:40,590 --> 00:07:42,610
So Graham's law applies.

104
00:07:43,360 --> 00:07:45,450
You've taken physics already?

105
00:07:45,530 --> 00:07:47,930
No, I just sort of
read up on my own.

106
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:51,990
I had to teach myself a lot
of stuff, too. Schools sucked
where I grew up.

107
00:07:52,070 --> 00:07:53,860
You go to public or private?

108
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:55,060
Public.

109
00:07:56,370 --> 00:08:00,030
Leak has to be in
the pulmonary veins
to get in my lungs, right?

110
00:08:00,110 --> 00:08:01,300
Yep.

111
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:03,040
I don't see anything. Do you?

112
00:08:03,110 --> 00:08:04,540
No.

113
00:08:04,610 --> 00:08:06,410
It doesn't make sense.

114
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:10,280
How can I have
a bloody effusion
without any bleeding?

115
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:14,020
(COUGHING)

116
00:08:28,340 --> 00:08:30,270
This is putrid.

117
00:08:30,340 --> 00:08:34,300
Put food-borne parasites
and infections
on the list to check on.

118
00:08:36,080 --> 00:08:37,980
I'll take the bedroom.

119
00:08:49,990 --> 00:08:52,320
Oh. Sorry, I didn't know
there was anyone.

120
00:08:52,390 --> 00:08:53,730
We were just...

121
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:55,820
Oh, God! I have a gun.

122
00:08:56,430 --> 00:08:58,920
Look, you can take
whatever you want.
My wallet's in my suit.

123
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:00,530
Freeze! Freeze!

124
00:09:00,600 --> 00:09:02,260
I'm calling the cops.

125
00:09:02,340 --> 00:09:06,170
Okay, you don't have a gun,
and you're not
calling the cops.

126
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:09,070
Oh, no, I'm calling the cops
unless you two
get out of here right now.

127
00:09:09,140 --> 00:09:13,600
"Unless"? Who calls the cops
unless a burglar
does something?

128
00:09:17,620 --> 00:09:19,310
You don't want to
have to explain the affair.

129
00:09:19,390 --> 00:09:21,190
We're not having an affair.

130
00:09:22,460 --> 00:09:24,430
He's got a ring. You don't.

131
00:09:24,490 --> 00:09:26,520
And judging from the state
of the kitchen downstairs

132
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:29,160
and the half-vacuumed bedroom,

133
00:09:29,230 --> 00:09:31,860
I'm guessing
you're a better lover
than you are a maid.

134
00:09:31,930 --> 00:09:35,630
Maid? You son of a bitch.

135
00:09:36,140 --> 00:09:39,900
I'm not a maid, okay?
This is my house, not his.

136
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:43,510
Sorry.
And what's wrong
with my kitchen?

137
00:09:43,580 --> 00:09:47,350
Nothing. We're sorry.
We're just here
to help Stevie.

138
00:09:48,420 --> 00:09:49,580
Who's Stevie?

139
00:09:49,650 --> 00:09:51,210
Your son?

140
00:09:55,320 --> 00:09:57,050
It was the address you gave.

141
00:09:57,130 --> 00:09:58,650
The ER must have
written it down wrong.

142
00:09:58,730 --> 00:10:00,960
Or you lied because
you don't want us to
talk to your parents.

143
00:10:01,030 --> 00:10:02,520
I gave you their
phone numbers.

144
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:05,260
You gave us some numbers.
We haven't been able to
reach anyone.

145
00:10:05,330 --> 00:10:06,600
I told you,
they must be in a conference.

146
00:10:06,670 --> 00:10:07,790
He's lying.

147
00:10:07,870 --> 00:10:09,460
Leah.

148
00:10:09,540 --> 00:10:12,530
He's Romany, a Gypsy.

149
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:16,430
So you don't have a home?

150
00:10:16,510 --> 00:10:17,980
Of course we do.

151
00:10:18,050 --> 00:10:21,020
What, next you're gonna ask me
about dancing around campfires

152
00:10:21,080 --> 00:10:24,710
and stealing children?
This is why
I don't tell people.

153
00:10:24,790 --> 00:10:29,380
They share everything with
each other and nothing with
the <i>gadje,</i> the outsiders.

154
00:10:29,460 --> 00:10:33,900
Sharing information with
outsiders has not gone
so well for my people.

155
00:10:34,630 --> 00:10:37,760
Right now you're making
yourself more vulnerable
by lying to us.

156
00:10:37,830 --> 00:10:41,230
You can't go to my house.
You'll pollute it.

157
00:10:41,300 --> 00:10:42,460
All we're gonna do
is look around.

158
00:10:42,540 --> 00:10:45,100
Your presence is enough.

159
00:10:46,210 --> 00:10:51,510
My parents take it seriously.
It's spiritual as much
as it is physical.

160
00:10:51,580 --> 00:10:52,670
You know where he lives?

161
00:10:52,750 --> 00:10:54,220
Don't.

162
00:10:54,280 --> 00:10:56,180
Look, I'll tell you
whatever you need to know.

163
00:10:56,250 --> 00:10:57,680
If we can't
trust your answers...

164
00:10:57,750 --> 00:11:00,780
I drink sometimes, okay?
I've smoked pot.

165
00:11:00,860 --> 00:11:04,690
I'll tell you anything,
the truth. You just...

166
00:11:06,290 --> 00:11:08,260
You can't go in my home.

167
00:11:09,970 --> 00:11:13,870
The pot wouldn't cause
a bleeding problem.
A pesticide on the pot could.

168
00:11:13,940 --> 00:11:15,870
Where did you get it?

169
00:11:15,940 --> 00:11:17,060
Some kid at school.

170
00:11:17,140 --> 00:11:19,400
Stevie. He got the pot
from me.

171
00:11:19,470 --> 00:11:21,500
He doesn't even go to school.
His parents made him drop out.

172
00:11:21,580 --> 00:11:23,640
I'm home-schooled.
He reads books.

173
00:11:23,710 --> 00:11:27,340
What else are you lying about?
Is your father really
a professor?

174
00:11:27,750 --> 00:11:29,110
He's a salesman.

175
00:11:29,180 --> 00:11:31,520
They buy and sell
anything they can
get their hands on.

176
00:11:31,590 --> 00:11:34,180
They? So you're with your dad
when he's making these deals?

177
00:11:34,260 --> 00:11:36,220
He was just in Chicago
a week ago.

178
00:11:36,290 --> 00:11:37,350
You fly?

179
00:11:37,430 --> 00:11:40,660
No, my dad's got a truck.

180
00:11:47,470 --> 00:11:48,960
You can't be serious.

181
00:11:49,040 --> 00:11:50,440
Actually, I can.

182
00:11:51,710 --> 00:11:54,010
See? It's my space.
I want it back.

183
00:11:54,080 --> 00:11:56,700
It's not your space.
It's the hospital's space,

184
00:11:56,780 --> 00:12:01,810
and the hospital thinks that
the person who's worse off
should get the better space.

185
00:12:01,880 --> 00:12:05,010
Your application for
a handicap space says
you can walk 50 yards.

186
00:12:05,090 --> 00:12:07,450
And Whitner's says
she can roll 50 miles

187
00:12:07,520 --> 00:12:09,650
between oil changes.
I can't change my leg.

188
00:12:09,730 --> 00:12:13,320
The space I moved you to
is only 46 yards away
from the front door.

189
00:12:13,400 --> 00:12:15,020
I measured. You'll be fine.
Great.

190
00:12:15,100 --> 00:12:19,060
So I can collapse four yards
into the lobby instead of
outside in the cold.

191
00:12:19,130 --> 00:12:21,000
As long as
it's not in my office.
Do you know who won

192
00:12:21,070 --> 00:12:25,100
the New York City Marathon
six years in a row?
Guy in a wheelchair.

193
00:12:25,170 --> 00:12:27,110
Then go get yourself one,
and leave me alone.

194
00:12:27,180 --> 00:12:30,010
Give me my space,
I'll be happy to
roll around all day.

195
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:33,010
You couldn't last one week
in a wheelchair.

196
00:12:33,080 --> 00:12:34,210
Wanna bet?

197
00:12:39,290 --> 00:12:40,380
What's wrong with you?

198
00:12:40,460 --> 00:12:42,920
Nothing that a week off
my feet won't solve.

199
00:12:42,990 --> 00:12:44,520
Venogram's negative. No leak.

200
00:12:44,590 --> 00:12:45,690
You mean you couldn't
find the leak.

201
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:46,850
Is your leg worse?

202
00:12:46,930 --> 00:12:49,260
No, my parking spot is.

203
00:12:49,330 --> 00:12:51,730
Blood is only made inside
the circulatory system,

204
00:12:51,800 --> 00:12:53,830
which means when we
find it outside...
There's no leak.

205
00:12:53,900 --> 00:12:55,560
I even checked lymphatics.
So you're gonna spend a week

206
00:12:55,640 --> 00:12:58,130
in a wheelchair just to get
a parking space
closer to the front door?

207
00:12:58,210 --> 00:12:59,730
Easier than chopping off
my legs.

208
00:12:59,810 --> 00:13:01,140
We've ruled out toxins
and drugs.

209
00:13:01,210 --> 00:13:05,040
Kind of. He's Romany.
Apparently, they feel the need
to keep secrets,

210
00:13:05,110 --> 00:13:06,810
so it's hard to know
anything for sure.

211
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:08,280
Yeah, he's also a human being,

212
00:13:08,350 --> 00:13:10,180
which means
you shouldn't be trusting him
to begin with.

213
00:13:10,250 --> 00:13:12,620
Stop relying on his answers
and find some on your own.

214
00:13:12,690 --> 00:13:14,180
It's a deep-vein thrombosis.

215
00:13:14,260 --> 00:13:17,050
The kid spent 16 hours
in the back seat
of an old pick-up.

216
00:13:17,130 --> 00:13:19,030
Causes a clot,
makes its way to his lungs.

217
00:13:19,090 --> 00:13:21,430
We should do an arteriogram,
find the clot,
bust it with TPA.

218
00:13:21,500 --> 00:13:22,590
Or we can find the leak.

219
00:13:22,660 --> 00:13:24,030
There's no leak.

220
00:13:24,100 --> 00:13:27,500
Hey, you can't yell at a guy
in a wheelchair.

221
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:31,400
This is a slow leak.
You've got to speed it up.

222
00:13:31,470 --> 00:13:33,200
Thin his blood.
Redo the venogram.

223
00:13:33,280 --> 00:13:34,770
That could cause
a massive bleed.

224
00:13:34,840 --> 00:13:37,400
Excellent.
Massive will be
even easier to find.

225
00:13:37,480 --> 00:13:40,810
Pardon me. I guess you guys
are gonna have to
get the next one.

226
00:13:45,090 --> 00:13:47,150
I thought you were
redoing the venogram.

227
00:13:47,220 --> 00:13:49,450
As soon as we're done
with the arteriogram.

228
00:13:50,390 --> 00:13:53,020
Okay, you're gonna feel
a little poke.

229
00:13:55,260 --> 00:13:57,360
Can you maybe do that?

230
00:13:57,430 --> 00:13:59,960
Don't worry. It's just
your leg. I don't have to
go any further than this.

231
00:14:00,040 --> 00:14:03,030
Take a look at this,
bones of your forearm.

232
00:14:03,910 --> 00:14:05,100
Radius and ulna.

233
00:14:05,170 --> 00:14:06,570
How about the wrist?

234
00:14:07,240 --> 00:14:11,370
Lunate, hamate, the...

235
00:14:11,880 --> 00:14:14,870
"Scared lovers
try positions
they can't handle."

236
00:14:18,220 --> 00:14:21,820
It's a mnemonic for
the wrist bones. It's the
only way I can remember them.

237
00:14:29,530 --> 00:14:31,060
(GROANING)

238
00:14:31,500 --> 00:14:32,860
FOREMAN: You okay?

239
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:36,030
My stomach.
Did you hit something?

240
00:14:36,100 --> 00:14:37,870
